{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472515"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1509"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1509"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.02,0.28,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82086"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"797"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28360"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a three-week history of a limp. The limp has been progressively worsening, and the child is now complaining of pain in his right leg, particularly around his knee. He is otherwise well with no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. He is usually quite active outdoors with his school friends and recalls no injury to the leg in the last few months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well but has an obvious limp when he walks. His pulse rate is 60/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is limitation of internal rotation and abduction of the right hip. There is no swelling nor tenderness. A plain X-ray of the right hip shows increased density of the capital femoral epiphysis and flattening of the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Developmental dysplasia of the hip","Juvenile idiopathic arthritis","Transient synovitis","Slipped capital femoral epiphysis","Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease, which is idiopathic avascular necrosis of the femoral head. The condition typically affects boys aged 4-10 years and presents with a limp and hip pain that may be referred to the knee. The radiological findings of increased density of the capital femoral epiphysis and flattening of the femoral head are pathognomonic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease\u003C/strong\u003E results from disruption of blood supply to the femoral head, leading to bone death and subsequent remodeling. The disease progresses through four stages: initial avascular necrosis, fragmentation, reossification, and healing with residual deformity. Clinical examination typically reveals limitation of hip abduction and internal rotation, as seen in this patient. Management depends on the age of the patient and extent of femoral head involvement, ranging from observation to containment surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient synovitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of acute hip pain in children and typically follows a viral illness. While it can present with a limp and hip pain, it is usually self-limiting, resolving within 7-10 days. The radiographic findings would be normal or show only a joint effusion, not the bony changes described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlipped capital femoral epiphysis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older children (10-16 years) and is more common in overweight adolescents. It presents with hip or knee pain and limited internal rotation. Radiographically, it appears as posterior and inferior displacement of the femoral head relative to the neck, not the increased density and flattening seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJuvenile idiopathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the hip joint but typically presents with morning stiffness, multiple joint involvement, and systemic symptoms such as fever and rash. Radiographic findings would show joint space narrowing and periarticular osteopenia rather than the changes described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopmental dysplasia of the hip\u003C/strong\u003E is typically diagnosed in infancy and presents with hip instability, asymmetric skin folds, and limited abduction. By age seven, it would have either been previously diagnosed or would present with a chronically dislocated hip and significant functional impairment, not an acute limp.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease typically presents as a limp with hip pain in boys aged 4-10 years with characteristic radiological findings of increased density and flattening of the femoral head.","Referred pain to the knee is common in hip pathology in children and should prompt examination of the hip.","Limitation of internal rotation and abduction of the hip are key examination findings in Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease."],"references":["Fabry G. Clinical practice: the hip from birth to adolescence. Eur J Pediatr. 2010 Feb;169(2):143-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19727813/","Gill KG. Pediatric hip: pearls and pitfalls. Semin Musculoskelet Radiol. 2013;17(3):328-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23787987/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82086"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1509"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82086"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-21T21:46:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-21T21:48:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1509"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relation